!! Engine adapter pattern

tw-graph discovers engines via `$tw.modules.createClassesFromModules("graphengine")`. Each engine exports a standard interface:

|!Export |!Purpose |
|`name` |Engine identifier (`"Cytoscape"`) |
|`properties` |Aggregated property schema from all `cytoscape-property` modules |
|`init(element, objects, options)` |Create Cytoscape instance, wire events, apply styles |
|`update(objects)` |Delta updates â€” add/update/remove nodes and edges |
|`destroy()` |Tear down Cytoscape instance and clean up timers |
|`processObjects(changes)` |Delegate to property handlers before engine update |
|`handleMessage(message, params)` |Route messages to handler modules |
|`forEachProperty(method, ...args)` |Invoke lifecycle method on all property handlers |

!! Property handler modules

Each `module-type: cytoscape-property` module declares properties and optional lifecycle hooks:

|!Module |!Responsibility |
|`id.js` |Assign IDs to nodes/edges |
|`defaults.js` |Apply initial defaults on first init |
|`events.js` |Map Cytoscape events to tw-graph callbacks with blur debouncing |
|`position.js` |Track node positions (x/y) for persistence |
|`nodes.js` |Node visual properties: label, size, shape, cluster |
|`edges.js` |Edge visual properties: arrows, stroke, width, label |
|`color.js` |Color mapping with luminance-based font contrast |
|`layout.js` |Hierarchical layout via breadthfirst |
|`physics.js` |COSE layout mapped from vis-network physics parameters |
|`interaction.js` |Zoom, pan, navigation controls |

!! Styling strategy

vis-network uses imperative options per node/edge. Cytoscape uses a declarative stylesheet.

The adapter uses a hybrid approach:

* ''Base stylesheet'' â€” built from graph-level defaults in `buildStylesheet()`, applied via `cy.style().fromJson()`
* ''Per-element overrides'' â€” applied via `ele.style({...})` after data updates, reading from `data._color`, `data._size`, etc.

This avoids expensive stylesheet rebuilds on every node change while keeping the declarative base clean.

!! Blur debouncing

vis-network fires `blurNode` based on canvas-internal hit testing â€” moving the mouse from a node to a DOM popup overlay doesn't trigger blur. Cytoscape fires `mouseout` immediately when the pointer leaves the node area for any reason.

The events handler debounces blur by 200ms and monitors `.graph-popup` elements via DOM event delegation. If the mouse enters a popup within the delay, the blur is cancelled.

